  "prompt": "Is it true that Socrates was considered as a prophet in Islam?",
  "response": "In Islamic tradition, Socrates is not widely recognized or considered as a prophet. While Islamic scholars and thinkers have engaged with Greek philosophy, including the works of Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle, these figures are typically regarded as philosophers rather than prophets.\n\nHowever, the Islamic Golden Age, particularly during the 8th to 14th centuries, saw a significant engagement with Greek philosophy. Muslim philosophers such as Al-Farabi, Avicenna (Ibn Sina), and Averroes (Ibn Rushd) were influenced by and built upon the works of Greek philosophers. They respected Socrates for his emphasis on ethics and virtue, and some Muslim scholars may have expressed admiration for him as a wise figure, but he is not considered a prophet within Islamic doctrine.\n\nIn Islam, the term \"prophet\" is reserved for those individuals who have received and conveyed divine revelation from God, such as the prophets mentioned in the Quran including Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and Muhammad, the last prophet in Islam.",
